title: For Sale:  BEAUTIFUL SPORTERIZED GERMAN DWM
postcontent: This is a beautifully sporterized 1909 Argentine Mauser manufactured in Germany for the Argentine Government. The maker of this rifle is supposedly from southern Pennsylvania however it is unknown the maker's name. Firearm is used in excellent condition, a few handling marks here and there on the stock. The metalwork is richly blued and does not show hardly any blemishes, bore is also bright and clean with strong rifling. In the mid 1880’s the Argentine army was using the Remington Rolling Block Rifle, after which they switched to the Model 1891 Mauser and finally, the Model 1909. The 1909 Argentine Mauser was manufactured under contract by DWM in Germany for the Argentine government and it was also later produced in Agentine factories. It's built on the large ring Mauser 98 style action and it was made in 4 versions, the 1909 Rifle, the 1909 sniper, 1909 Cavalry, and the 1909 Mountain Carbine, each of the last three in limited numbers. It is not known which configuration this rifle originally started out as.Caliber: .30-06 SpringfieldBarrel: 24" Sporter ContourLength of Pull: 14" Overall Length: 45.25" Weight: 7.9 Lbs Stock: High Grade Walnut with Monte Carlo cheek piece and rosewood forend and grip cap.Mounts: Steel Redfield 1 Piece Base and Medium 1" Rings

title: For Sale:  Western Auto Revelation m120  22lr
postcontent: Okay so this is an interesting gun.It's a Western Auto Supply "Revelation" model 120.These were made for Western Auto by Marlin in the 60s, 70s and 80s.It's basically a Marlin model 60 that came with different wood. This one looks like it came somewhere in the 70s since it have the longer magazine tube.It's a semi-autos, tube fed 22lr.I am told these also can shoot 22 magnums. But do you own research.These are known to be accurate and reliable.The rifle looks like it's in awesome shape... The bad part is... The previous owner was a jackass and broke/cracked the stock he just sawed it off behind the hand grip.  Apparently with the intention to repair it... I know... I know... I thought the same thing... How about just using wood glue instead of chopping anything up?But he chopped it and never fixed it.So it will need a new stock or you can just shoot it without cheek weld. (It's a 22. There's no recoil)I intended to fix it up and give my 11 year old something to practice with but then I won a ruger 10-22 at an NRA auction.  Needless to say he uses that and I haven't gotten another stock either.I did look into stocks for it though. There are a LOT of options.  You can get a used one online almost anywhere for $20. You can spend $30-$40 and get a tactical looking one with an adjustable stock. And they even make target/precision stocks for these. They are more pricey though.Any stock that would fit a Marlin model 60 or 90 that is tube-fed will fit with no modifications.I have never fired it.I took it apart to inspect, clean, lube it. And it all looks great (I don't think this rifle was fired very much).I just don't need it.  Maybe someone could find an original stock from Western Auto Supply and have a nice little piece of history.  I'm setting the price at $100 and that's negotiable.So $100 OBO.I don't like selling things so I'll probably sell to the first person who shows up with a realistic offer.I prefer texts or emails.52 O,  2 72 , O2 20

title: For Sale/Trade:  M1 Garand, Springfield 1943
postcontent: have a 1943 Springfield M1 Garand for sale or trade. This rifle has excellent rifling inside it's barrel and is in very good mechanical condition. It shoots very straight and is 30/06 in caliber. The wooden stock is in good condition with no wood missing. The wood stock carries a very used look and represents itself as you would expect from a former WWII battlefield firearm. The metal is all rust free and has no issues on it's parkerized finish. This weapon is extremely collectable, especially being a 1943 Springfield. The numbers do not match throughout the rifle and to find one that does is more then a rare occurrence as they all were assembled of parts from millions of guns off the assembly line after WWII and the Korean war. This weapon has obviously seen battle and been a part of WWII, Korea and possibly the beginning of Vietnam. I have fired this rifle and can assure you it fires very well, and hits the target. It ejects fine and never jams. The firing pin hits the primer dead center and in the same location every single time. It has the original rifle sling as well. Bayonet does come with the rifle and I am positive it's a US Military bayonet but I am not positive it's the original bayonet that was issued with this rifle. Although it is the bayonet and sheath I received when I took possession of the weapon. Rifle comes with 3 ammo clips as well. Buy with confidence and I will consider any firearm trades as well. As for trades I will look at anything as for rifles and pistols but I prefer tactical weapons. I may even consider a four wheeler if it's reliable and looks nice.
